[[ch09-handbook-fellowship-of-the-ring]]
== Handbook: A Fellowship Of The Ring

This chapter is about a quest to find thirty people, a fellowship, and then to practice trusting those people creating a ring of trust: a Fellowship Of the Ring.

We need to learn to society again. Sociologists have long documented the breakdown of society since 1900.

1. Breakdown of the family and work starting in 1900.
2. Breakdown of the neighborhood in 1950.
3. Elimination of the stranger in the 1970s. The Eagles song, "New Kid In Town", was the last pop song about a stranger. :)
4. Final family breakdown in the 1990s due to the microwave oven eliminating family meals.
5. Loss of bowling and bowling alleys virtually overnight in the 1990s.

Societies transitioning from 90% direct agriculture labor before 1900 to only 2% by 1980 radically destroyed previous culture leaving nothing durable behind. New technologies constantly being introduced continuously destroys society faster than societies can adapt. That's the challenge.

Prior to 1900 there were no roads, no indoor plumbing, no telephones and no electricty. People worked the land to put food on the table via hunting and farming. There weren't grocery stores on every corner. A nearby railroad may have provided flour and such in some general stores, but certainly no packaged food. We had to cook. Life in 1900 would have been easily recognizable to those who founded the US in 1789. Not today.

Technology constantly upsets the social apple cart. Today society is once again being threatened by AI where the large corporation Oracle just recently announced laying off 30,000 people due to AI. In fact, AI corporations are wanting to eliminate millions of existing jobs. 

Today we do not trust. We do not trust the government. We do not trust the media. We do not trust schools. We do not trust vaccines. We do not trust AI. It would be easier to state what we do trust, which is not much.

We need to learn to trust again, to society again. This is why our first quest is called, "A Fellowship Of The Ring".

Welcome adventurer! Would you like to go on a quest to help Thorin and his party of Dwarves reclaim their ancestral home and treasure, which has been seized by the dragon Smaug?

A little too much? How about just a quest to learn to dance?

.Twonks Tap
[#img-tap,link=https://irreni.social/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/twonks-tap.jpg] 
image::book/twonks-tap.jpg[Twonks - Tap Your Card,400,500] 

Any quest of significance requires a company, a fellowship. But how big? Well, it depends on the roles needed. In "The Hobbit", Gandalf recruited Bilbo as a thief. Or, in moder.n Dungeons and Dragons terminology, a rogue.

I started playing D&D when it first came out in the early 70s. The standard company size was four people. Generally something like a fighter, a thief, a magic user, and a cleric. But that's kinda small. For example, with that configuration there is no ranged or bow capacity. So perhaps the party would have a fighter, a thief, an archer, a magic user and a cleric.

When it comes to tap dancing even a quest to learn how to dance would require a dance instructor and dance partners.

But tap dancing and dragon hunting are not what we are about here. We are about New Democracy.

Our party size in New Democracy is a fixed thirty people. The size is not based solely upon the roles needed.
Why?

First, thirty seems kinda too big doesn't it? Well, continuing with our example of a D&D party of size five then New Democracy requires we double that for redundancy. I mean you are kinda screwed if your D&D party healer dies. Or even the fighter. So, we doubled the size of the party to ten for redundancy. Further, we are building society and not adventuring. That means we will have dependents such as children, elderly parents and the infirm. So we'll double our size ten to size twenty to include one dependent for every adventurer. Finally, we don't live in medieval times now. Today a company would need more than five roles. At a minimum we'd need a doctor, a lawyer, communications, marketing, computing, engineering, and various support roles such as cooking. Our adventurer team size then easily grows to size ten. We double that for redundancy and we get twenty. We double twenty to include dependents and we get forty. However, we cap the number to thirty as a convention. 

Thirty is a convention and a standard. It is not a science or some ideal role count derived number. It is mutually agreed upon for no other reason than to have a standard. Think of thirty like the size of a car today. Cars are designed to fit roads. Roads were initially designed to fit horse-drawn wagons. We're still driving wagons.

The benefit of a convention is that we can build cars and roads anywhere in the world and guarantee new cars, old cars, and cars from different countries can drive on the same roads. We can still drive on roads over one-hundred years old. The fixed size thirty convention fills likewise purpose.

So adventurer, your quest to begin New Democracy is to establish a fellowship of a ring of trust of fixed size thirty people. We need to rebuild society with better trust. And we want this new society to withstand new technology continuously being foisted on us. The quest then includes a requirement to also build a durable society. A robust and resilient society that can permanently withstand the relentless upheavals of new technology.

This new trusting and durable society defines New Democracy. A society of the people, by the people, and for the people. Permanently. New Democracy uses a mesh design to achieve this goal, to withstand the test of technological upheaval. A mesh design is a convention fixed size thirty mesh nodes combined with projects for mesh nodes to work together. The MGO size convention is simple enough to scale infinitely in time and space. It is simply enough for most humans to understand.

This first quest of establishing a fellowship of size thirty represents one of only two components within New Democracy design: MGOs and projects. MGOs, or micro-governing organizations, are fellowships of fixed size thirty. They are the new country, the new nation. These new nations coordinate using projects. Projects then are the second of two New Democracy components.

New Democracy is not about establishing a government. New Democracy is about establishing a trusting society. Old Democracy has taught us that a separate government sitting atop various coordinating societies doesn't build up social trust, it destroys trust.

So the responsible thing is to establish a society and call it New Democracy.

In some very real sense an MGO is a castle with a moat. Alligators protect the moat. These castles establish two boundaries:

1. Individual trust within thirty people.
2. Technological advancement moat for external trust


Anyway, back to our quest to establish a fellowship of the ring of trust. This means we need to rebuild family units. We need to rebuild the neighborhood. We need to bring back the stranger concept.

An MGO as a nation means those inside the MGO are personally trusted. Everyone outside of the MGO not so much. Of course MGOs will have other MGO neighbors. This will begin providing natural layers of trust that, like an onion, will have many many rings of ever larger size of trust. These rings are called projects they coordinate groups of MGOs.

Okay, so this chapter mission is clear: form an MGO. How do we do this? Quests say very little about how. However, let's discuss some options as both real things you can do and food for thought if they don't apply to your situation.

Legal advantage. First, form a corporation. Corporations are people legally in Old Democracies. We are going to use that to our advantage. We are going to start "for life" corporations. These corporations are for supporting life. They will have external business to make profits. This "for life" company will have various capabilities such as a medical bay, a dental bay, a legal team, a software team, and a manufacturing team. Establishing these "micro-teams" of one-or-two people enables the MGO to have an expert skill to trust the outside world. The MGO trusts its internal teams then these teams provide the expertise of trust for the external world.

Baby steps. Start with just two people. From a corporation of two people. Create a set of by-laws for the company that represents your fellowship's "constitution". Publish the by-laws/constitution publicly and solicit new members. Use existing communication tools such as Discord, Slack. MS Teams, Facebook, What's App, or even smoke signals :) to communicate daily. Gradually build your fellowship one person at a time to thirty people.

Pool resources. Corporations allow us to pool resources. This is a fundamental component of trust. We share Netflix passwords with our twenty-nine new friends. :) Corporations buy things at a discount. Corporations buy Internet service cheaper than buying that same service as one individual multiplied thirty times pricing. 

Trust exercise. Trust is a talent that requires daily practice. This is no different than say a sport like tennis where an individual has to practice daily to maintain skill level. Trust is no different except it is a group exercise. One example from my personal life comes from World of Warcraft, an MMO game. Warcraft has raids that can have as many as forty people. An MGO could have all its members create a guild, or team, in Warcraft and play raid as a team. Or your MGO will create bowling teams of five and go bowling. Play card games. The point is trust needs daily workouts. Establish those trust exercises.

Side quests. Side quests are needed to build trust. For example, we need bowling alleys in order to bowl. If your fellowship wants to bowl as trust exercise then building a new bowling alley may be needed. Another side quest is academic. Trust can be taught in school. Establish public schools and online courses to teach people how to trust. Another side quest is filling roles instead of finding them. If some new member signs up to fill a role they have no experience in then the fellowship may need to send them to get a standard education for being a nurse or something like that. 

Side note. Okay, the trust school may seem weird. We could learn something from the wizard Gandalf from the book, "The Hobbit". You see, one night the fellowship was under threat of being eaten by dire wolves as night was about to set in. Gandalf devised a scheme to shelter in a local Giant's house. The only problem is that giants don't like dwarves. So Gandalf devised a scheme to gradually introduce the twelve dwarves two-by-two. Giants love stories and Gandalf was a great storyteller. He and Bilbo first went into the Giant's house for protection. The Giant agreed for the price of a story. As Gandalf proceeded into the story he would whistle and then introduce the Giant to two more dwarves. The Giant being enthralled with the story begrudgingly agreed to two more dwarves spending the night. Eventually all twelve dwarves were safely inside. That's a lesson in trust.

Enjoy. Probably one of the most quintessential observations made about Western society is that in the process of making a living we forget how to live. We don't want to duplicate these worst aspects of Old Democracy. We want to ensure that all aspects of fellowship life makes a living and also lives.

MGO community. Join or create a community for MGOs. MGO teams can build libraries of information recording best practices. MGOs can support each other by trading success and failure stories. Existing MGOs can help new MGOs get started by acting as training officers.

We've reviewed a few suggestions above. The Earth has eight-billion people. The suggestions here for how to create an MGO successfully are just that. Corporations being legal people will suffice on some parts of the Earth and not others. Not everyone bowls, don't ask me why. Hopefully, though, the suggestions provided enough food for thought such that you feel like, "Yeah, I can do this." For you to feel like, "Yeah, you know, it sounded weird in the beginning but now I get it. We are just forming groups to take advantage of group benefits missing today." For you to feel like, "Yeah, I don't understand New Democracy but I do understand just this one thing, forming an MGO."
New Democracy is engineering and any part can be taken advantage of as a part. An MGO is one part.

So adventurer, are you ready to go on a quest? A quest to create a fellowship of a ring of trust? The overall objective is to rebuild society.

The following chapters will talk about common quests for MGOs to build out the MGO. Quests like buying land for a campus of thirty people. Or establishing buildings for storage of food and water. Quests for building power plants to a campus of thirty people.

Enjoy!
